Historically, sampling for orthopterans in the Malay Peninsula (including Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore ) is not evenly distributed (
). For the katydids (Tettigonioidea) from Peninsular Malaysia , considerably more material has been examined and more species have been described from the state of Pahang and other northern states of Peninsular Malaysia (e.g.,
;
, 1998b;
,
). Likewise, there was also concerted effort to document the orthopteran diversity in Singapore more recently (e.g.,
,
, 2017;
). Conversely, in the state of Johor (south of Peninsular Malaysia and north of Singapore ), far fewer information about the orthopteran species is available.

